The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                 NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 London, Jan. 10 (PTI): An Indian call centre employee, who sent a series of amorous texts and a voice message to an English customer of British Telecommunications, has been disciplined by the company.           
	The Portsmouth-based female customer complained to BT about the messages that amounted to electronic stalking. The microbiologist had applied for a landline connection in December. She received a call and gave her details but soon began receiving text messages from the operator saying he was attracted to her voice.           e message read: Hello, we spoke two hours ago..... To be honest I got attracted towards you and your wonderful voice. Can i be ur friend? The messages were peppered with kisses, and wished her sweet dreams.                   
	 Washington (PTI): An executive of a valve manufacturing company in the US allegedly bribed officials of the Maharashtra State Electricity Board to bag contracts between March 2003 and 2007, the US government has charged. Italian Mario Covino, an executive of the unnamed company, has pleaded guilty to the charges of paying $1 million to officials of several state-owned entities worldwide.                   
	 Mumbai (PTI): Seven Indians and their vessel MV Delight, hijacked from the Gulf of Aden in November, have been freed by pirates and they are safe, the directorate-general of shipping said.                   
	 London (PTI): The family of an 11-year-old Sikh boy who was found abandoned at a bus stop here in March 2008 has been traced in Punjab. Officials have discovered after DNA tests that the uncle of Gurinder Singh, who cannot speak English, lives in Hoshiarpur in Punjab.                   
	 New Delhi (PTI): CISF personnel opened fire at IGI Airport on Saturday to stop two men who tried to flee after they were spotted near the boundary wall. Sachin and Hemant Malik, both property dealers, were drinking liquor on a railway track outside exit gate No.14. They were released later.                                                                                                                           
